                           </table><center>  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - NECROMANCER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>LEVEL'S 1 - 8 AS A HERETIC (ERUDITE NECROMANCER)</font> - <small>Xumbraxa, Torvonnilous</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><B>Level 1</B>
<P>
You will start off in the city of heretics, Paineel, despite the fact that it may say your only choice for a starting city is Erudin.  Scribe your spells and see your guildmaster Coriante Verisue... give her the note in your inventory and hail her.  You'll get your guild tunic--a dirty robe, and she'll send you on an errand to collect bat wings and snake fangs.  The necromancer guild called the Abattior, and is the gated structure with ghosts wandering in and out, chanting spookily.  If you don't know how to scribe or equip items, do the tutorial. :)  You also have a bone key in your inventory.  This acts as a slight light source as long as you don't have it inside a container like a backpack... you need this key to leave Paineel.  If you lose your key somehow, target one of the guards and say 'I need a key.' and they will give you one.  Also, in the necromancer guild, target Auhirk Siet'ka and say 'I understand common' and he will give you a small bag and send you on a task... don't worry about the task (unless you really want to do it)--the main thing is that you get a free container, so you don't have to make as many runs to the store/bank early on.  Next, have somebody show you how to leave town and find the 'newbie yard', or download a map of the town from a web site.
<P>
The newbie yard of Paineel is one of the easiest newbie areas in the world.  There are very few aggressive creatures (only Noclin's pet and undead rats, which usually aren't around) and the area is too small for even a blind erudite to get lost in... plus, there are always PLENTY of things to kill.
<P>
Start by doing Coriante's wings & fangs quest and kill black bats and moss snakes.  Killing them souldn't be too difficult... just cast Minor Shielding on yourself, and run up to an enemy and autoattack and cast Lifetap on your foe every once in a while (time it so you cast immediately after you are attacked, to reduce the chance that you are interupted.)  Once you collect 4-8 of each of these items, give them to Coriante in pairs.  She should give you two spell scrolls: Cavorting Bones and Locate Corpse, both are good spells.
<P>
<B>Level 2-3</B>
<P>
You probably advanced to level 2 while killing bats and snakes, or after you turned in the wings and fangs to Coriante.  Cavorting Bones is your first 'pet' spell... it summons a minor skeleton to fight for you.  Here are the pet commands:
<P>
/pet attack - Pet attacks whatever you have targetted.
<BR>
/pet guard here - Pet stays where it is and attacks anything aggressive to you that comes across its path... if you are attacked, the pet will stop guarding and run to assist you.
<BR>
/pet back off - Commands your pet to stop attacking, but this only works if neither you or your pet is being attacked.  In other words, it only works if your foe is stunned or on the run.  Useful because if your pet gets the last hit, it takes experience.
<BR>
/pet follow me - Your pet follows you.
<BR>
/pet guard me - Your pet follows you.
<BR>
/pet get lost - Your pet kills itself.
<BR>
/pet sit down - Your pet crumbles into a heap of bones and recovers HP faster (although your pet already recovers HP really fast.)
<BR>
/pet stand up - Your pet reforms back into the standing position and stands where it is (guarding) until you tell it to follow you.
<P>
You should make a set of hot keys for all the importants: attack, back off, follow, guard.  Also note that you can command your pet orally by targetting it and speaking aloud (so don't say 'I hate it when I *get lost* in this forest' when you have your pet targgetted, or it will think you are telling it to get lost.)
<P>
On equipping your pet: you can give your pet a weapon (the same way you give an NPC an item.)  Weapons work somewhat unusually for pets however.  First off, your pet will always attack with a delay of 30 (even if the weapon is faster or slower.)  Your pet's barehanded attack power depends on its level (I think the best Cavorting Bones pet attacks for a maximum of 10 hp,) unless you give it a weapon, and then the max damage it can do per hit will be the weapon's DMG times two (so if you give it a 6 dmg, it will do a max of 12 damage) UNLESS the max damage for the weapon is lower than what the pet can do barehanded (so you can never make your pet weaker by giving it a weapon.)  Basically, you can increase the amount of damage your pet does by giving it a weapon with DMG greater than 6 or so at this level, but things should be easy enough in the yard that you don't need to equip your pet.  There is no way to get weapons back from your pet.
<P>
At this point, kill nothing but decaying skeletons in the newbie yard.  There are always plenty of them to kill, and while the experience is not as good as beetles, it is much better money.  You will get a ton of bone chips, which you can either immediately sell (which is still decent money with all the chips you get--you'll get about 2.5 gp per stack,) or you can sell them to a player later for 1-2pp (nobody on Odus buys bone chips because Odus is desolate and because they could always just go to the newbie yard,) or you can save them for yourself later so you don't have to go on bone hunts or pay lower level characters for 'em.  Or you can do some combination. :)  The skeletons also drop rusty weapons and cracked staffs--the staffs sell for more than a platinum (and make a decent weapon for yourself at this point and look better than a dagger.)  The skeletons also sometimes drop rusty halberds, which I recommend you stash in the bank for later equipping your pets (they are 10 DMG weapons, but only sell for about 2 gp.)  Buy yourself a heavy backpack or two when you can afford them and get rid of the quest pouch you got earlier.
<P>
<B>Level 4</B>
<P>
If you did as I recommended and hunted only decaying skeletons, you now have enough money to buy most (if not all) of your level 1/4 spells (which are available in the necromancer's guild.)  At this point, I recommend you keep killing decaying skeletons in the newbie yard (the experience is somewhat poor, but the money is still useful and you still have plenty of action.)  Use your new pet spell and practice your spells by casting Life Spike and Poison Bolt often, even though you and your pet are killing the skeletons easily enough that you don't need help from the spells... you want to cast them anyway to keep your spell skills up.   At this point, you can probably kill Noclin's pet when you see it wandering the yard.  I recommend you do so and return the rotting femur to Noclin, to get a fairly decent weapon--Noclin's femur (it is 5/35 dmg/dly, magic, -5 charisma and procs Sicken at level 10, 1hb, if I recall correctly.)
<P>
By the end of level 4 you should have quite a bit of spare platinum.  Enter Sinfully Handsome and buy yourself a full set of cloth armor (except tunic) to get your AC a bit of a boost.  Also, buy a Sr. Apprentice's robe from your guild (AC 6, +2 mana, looks better than the dirt-soiled deal) and you might want to get a staff from your guild as well (5/28, I think.)  All that should cost you around 12 platinum, which you ought to be able to afford rather easily.
<P>
<B>Level 5</B>
<P>
Time to leave the newbie yard.  You could still get experience there from killing fire beetles, but its probably better that you start familiarizing yourself with Toxxulia forest.  Buy yourself a large lantern first and put away that key, the forest is DARK, especially at night.
<P>
There are two kobold camps in the forest, as well as a log by which a magician named Shintar spawns, all in close proximity to each other (I recommend you download a map and give it a glance to learn the general layout of the forest.)  Various creatures roam the forest such as briar snakes, widow hatchings, spiderlings, infected rats and fire beetles.  The tougher aggressive creatures would be the kobold sentries, shaman and skeletons (not decaying skeletons, just "skeletons.")  The shamans always stay camped at their camps.  A note on shaman, they always seem to resist your Poison Bolt/Disease Cloud spells, so don't bother with those--use Clinging Darkess and Lifespike instead.  At this point, kill various creatures and go on kobold camp raids, and kill Shintar.  Just be wary of the skeletons and the infected rats who assist them, and remember that Paineel is located to the south.
<P>
Note that the miner skeletons in the Paineel-Toxxulia tunnel aren't guards... they will assist their fellow skeletons and attack you if a skeleton follows you into the tunnel (most NPCs, including your pet will turn away and run before you reach the tunnel though.)  You can give the useless caps you find off kobold scouts to one of these skeletons for some experience, faction and a little item (a small gem, bone chips, zombie skin, or possibly a minor weapon or shield.)
<P>
Also, there is a druid ring located across the river North of Paineel.  Find out where it is so you can go there to sell stuff without having to zone back into Paineel, it can be a time-saver.
<P>
<B>Level 6</B>
<P>
Pretty much the same as level 5, except now you don't gain experience from quite as many things, but are having an easier time surviving and navigating Toxxulia.  You ought to be able to raid the kobold camps pretty effectively alone (with your pet,) so just do that repeatedly and kill Shintar when you notice him by the log.
<P>
<B>Level 7</B>
<P>
Level 7 kind of sucks. ;)  I recommend that if you can find somebody else who is level 6/7 to team up with, that you do so and kill the heretic pet that spawns near the Paineel zone tunnel in Toxxulia, and do kobold raids between spawns.  You don't get experience from most of the critters or kobolds anymore (only some briar snakes and some kobold sentries/shaman) so this level is pretty rough.
<P>
If you're forced to go it alone, I recommend that you get rid of your pet and use Sense Undead to try to find skeletons (not the miner ones though) and solo them (no pet,) killing blue conning kobolds and snakes that you encounter as well.  This can be annoying though because too often your Sense Undead picks up the wandering heretic pet, which is difficult to kill alone.
<P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
And that's it.  You still ought to have enough money left over to buy many of your level 8 spells--Walking Bones, your pet upgrade, Gather Shadows so you can sneak through Erudin and get to Qeynos, Deadeye so you can see in the dark, Lesser Shielding because more AC/HP is never a bad thing, Vampiric Embrace because you are still doing melee at this point, Dark Pact to lower your downtime, Mend Bones so you can heal that level 9 pet you spent 5 minutes trying to summon, Ward Undead, because its cheap and because it hurts undead REAL GOOD--but you'll have to practice your evocation a lot, ect.  Most of your level 8 spells have their use and are quite nice.  You may want to stick around in Odus for a bit longer, as much as you are starting to hate the place.  You can practice Ward Undead on decaying skeletons in the yard and make enough money to get all your level 8 spells (as well as stockpile bone chips,) and you might want to do Antus's quest to kill Agilthn Dasmore, the fisherman.
<P>
I leave the rest for your to figure out. ;)</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
